# C# Standards

## No empty try-catch

Never leave empty `catch` blocks. Either remove the try-catch or add real error handling (e.g. log, rethrow with context, or handle meaningfully).

```csharp
// BAD
try { DoWork(); } catch (Exception) { }

// GOOD: remove if not needed
DoWork();

// GOOD: add handling
try { DoWork(); }
catch (Exception ex)
{
    _logger.LogError(ex, "DoWork failed");
    throw;
}
```

## Braces for all control flow

Always use braces for `if`, `else`, `for`, `foreach`, `while`, and `using` bodies, even when the body is a single statement.

```csharp
// BAD
if (flag) DoSomething();
foreach (var x in items) Process(x);

// GOOD
if (flag) { DoSomething(); }
foreach (var x in items) { Process(x); }
```

## XML Documentation

Summaries for public classes and interfaces must not be empty. If a documentation comment exists, the `<summary>` tag must contain meaningful text. See `.cursor/rules/xml-documentation.mdc` for details.

## One file per class

Prefer one file per class, interface, or struct. Each top-level type should generally have its own file. See `.cursor/rules/one-file-per-class.mdc` for details.
